    <h5 class="mt-8" style="font-size: 1.3em; font-weight: bold;">2) Breaking Media Silos with Consensus Building</h5>
    <img src="/assets/images/silos.jpg" width="500" alt="Silos" />
    <a class="underline" href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/14617207@N00/4872111479">Silo Canister</a> in Indiana. &nbsp;&nbsp; Photo Credit: <a class="underline" href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/14617207@N00/">Alan Berning</a><br /><br />
    <p>I would like to make the CiteIt database freely available so that a broad array of people to analyze it and develop aggregators.</p>
    
    <h5 class="text-green-600" style="font-size: 1.05em; font-weight: bold;">Open Data &gt; A New Generation of Aggregators</h5>
    <p>I would hope that a new generation of search engines (or <strong>aggregators</strong>) could locate the <strong>top ranked citation</strong> comments associated with citation fragmnents and develop innovative user interfaces.</p>
    
    <h5 class="text-green-600" style="font-size: 1.05em; font-weight: bold;">Viewing the Top Results from Many Silos</h5>
    <p>One desirable feature would be to <strong>classify and group</strong> quotes of a particular type together and display the <strong>top quotes of each group</strong>.</p>

    <p>Surfacing citations from accross the internet has the potential to <strong>reduce the polarization</strong> that results when individuals <strong>cluster into their own homogenous groups (silos)</strong>.</p>

    <h5 style="font-size: 1.3em; font-weight: bold;">3) Civil Conversations</h5>

    <p>If CiteIt develops as a community, work sould be done to intentially work to
    <a class="underline" target="_blank" href="https://onbeing.org/civil-conversations-project/">build Civil Conversations</a>,
    as healthy communities take time and intentionality to develop.</p>


